Of these the latter said that the soul μηδὲν εἶναι παρὰ τό πως ἔχειν τὸ σῶμαε the former was a musician, and Lucr. seems (cf. 1. 132) to have had him chiefly in his mind. As this theory of course implies the mortality of the soul, one might have expected Lucr. to view it with more indulgence.
